00186 //============================================================================
00187 // STRING HASH TABLES
00188 //============================================================================
00189 /*
00190 djb2
00191 
00192 this algorithm (k=33) was first reported by dan bernstein many years ago in
00193 comp.lang.c. another version of this algorithm (now favored by bernstein) uses
00194 xor: hash(i) = hash(i - 1) * 33 ^ str[i]; the magic of number 33 (why it works
00195 better than many other constants, prime or not) has never been adequately
00196 explained.
00197 
00198 Adapted from: http://www.cse.yorku.ca/~oz/hash.html
00199 */
00200 inline int Hash(const char* pch)
00201 {
00202         unsigned long zHash = 5381;
00203         int ch;
00204 
00205         while ((ch = *pch++) != 0){
00206                 zHash = ((zHash << 5) + zHash) + ch; /* zHash * 33 + c */
00207         }
00208 
00209         return zHash;
00210 }
